Professor Sahai's repeated comments on this board encouraging students to take 127 and 126 before 189 have contributed to a massive enrollment spike in the former two and a sizable decrease in demand for the latter. As such, would it be possible for Professor Sahai and the department to reallocate some of the TA support for 189 to the 126 and 127 professors? 

I find it strange that these two "foundational" classes, as Professor Sahai calls them, have barely 110 spots yet 189, his own class, has 400 seats with at least 140 still open as of this post.

The sections aren't empty. The sections have students enrolled in them.

It's not an uncommon practice for the number of seats across the sections to be larger than the number of seats for the lecture. This allows students to have greater flexibility in which section they attend. The class enrollment is still limited by the number of seats for the lecture.

I'm not trying to be sassy, I'm genuinely interested in whether I am misunderstanding the way the seating for these classes works

To my knowledge, grad students can't enroll in 127. They have to enroll in 227A, just as undergrads have to enroll in 127.

Think of it as a single class, that has seats split among two populations (undergrads don't have a stronger claim to the course than graduate students do). The department needs to reserve seats for graduate students, who enroll in classes later. But the open seats do get shifted around / balanced as necessary.

http://classes.berkeley.edu/content/2018-spring-eecs-127-001-dis-201 and others show that there is no space on the waitlist for any discussion, hence you can't waitlist.

It doesn't matter that there are open spots in the sections if there is no open space in lecture.

It doesn't matter that there is open space on the lecture waitlist if there is no open space for the section waitlists.

You have to be able to enroll in both, or waitlist in both.
Also remember the class is combined section with 227AT, so the open lecture seats are reserved for graduate students and not open to undergrads

Will EE127 be expanded?

Does the entire situation not deserve to be mocked? How can 189 turn away so many students for not having the necessary training, and then the EECS Department not have enough resources to provide that training? This is the sort of catch-22 that we should not have to expect from what is supposed to be one of the top ranked computer science programs.

I wouldn't attack this student. Seiji is trying to make a point and I agree that the class should be expanded. It's quite unfortunate how Berkeley students have to go through this every single semester.

I'd like to point out that the situation with 189 is mostly caused by Sahai (frankly) and so pinning this on the department seems unreasonable. Instead I think the department is being very cooperative with us with our requests to expand enrollment (at least for 126).

Also I'd like to clarify: please don't take my statement above to mean that I agree or disagree with Sahai's policies. Regardless of my opinions, the increased demand for 126/127 is real and we'll do our best to accommodate.
Does CS189 turn away students for not having the necessary training"? I thought the only requirements were the CS61 series and EE16/B, and those weren't even hard requirements.

Prereqs are usually never enforced. 126 and 127 are also not listed officially as prerequisites, but a professor, Sahai, has been emphasizing their importance on this Piazza in what seems like hundreds of posts, hence the high demand.

My comment was meant more as a general remark on the absurdity of Berkeley life rather than an attack on any particular actor, but I still think it's fair to say that the department could have done more to anticipate this spike in demand given how much Sahai has been pushing for it on Piazza and in his own class.

history.content: Is it possible for these classes to expand? Many student want to take both classes to prepare for CS188 and CS189, but there were only 110 spots in EECS126 and EECS127 is already full for undergraduates. These classes were lauded highly for their importance, but only a few people have been able to enroll in them before they reached capacity. Can anything be done to allow more students to take these classes?
